  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Campaigns addressing Gender Norms in COVID-19</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Campaign Addressing Gender Norms in COVID -19 is a joint initiative of Oxfam in the Philippines and Investing in Women (IW) which seeks to study and influence the prevailing gender norms among urban millennials (18 -40 years old) who are working in the business process outsourcing (BPO) industry in the Philippines. The campaign aims to influence the policy discourse on post -COVID -19 recovery measures in collaboration with policymakers, regulators and private sector leaders in the BPO industry.  These campaign initiatives were meant to create an enabling environment where key decision -makers would consider the project&apos;s recommended interventions and post -pandemic economic recovery measures through the promotion of positive deviance in gender norms on shared care work and breadwinning among urban millennials. To attain the target objectives, the following interventions will be undertaken: A. Action Research  A qualitative inquiry to (1) surface gender norms or narratives on unpaid care work and breadwinning among urban millennials in the midst of the pandemic; (2) highlight how they have challenged these; and (3) determine what various stakeholders can do to support and promote shared responsibilities in Unpaid Care Work (UCW) and breadwinning. Focus group discussions, and key informant interviews will be conducted to supplement findings from the Social Norms Attitudes and Practices Survey (SNAPS) and SNAPS 2.0 and to inform a robust social media campaign.  B. Social Media Campaign  Oxfam shall employ social media campaign strategies based on solid experience and lessons from two successful social media campaigns on unpaid care work. These are &quot;I laba Yu&quot; campaign and &quot;How I care Campaign.&quot; The objectives of this campaign would be to: &#x2022; Engage a community of influencers towards deepening knowledge on positive deviance on UCW and breadwinning among urban millennials;  &#x2022; Create and strengthen partnerships among and between social media influencers, private sector and</narrative>
  </description>
